Part II - Factors affect students' academic performance and learning time¶

by Anh Nguyen¶

Investigation Overview¶

This project aims to explore whether certain background factors can affect students' academic performance and how much time they spend learning.

We will first take a look at the distribution of scores and learning time. Then we will see the impact of background factors such as gender, OECD membership, parents'education on students' performance and study time.

Dataset Overview¶

PISA is the global survey that assesses the competencies of 15-year-old students in reading, mathematics and science, as well as to understand their family backgrounds and educational systems. The dataset has 485,490 student records grouped in 636 columns. Here, I only focused on some features of interest such as country of residence, OECD membership, student's gender, parents' education level; academic performance on Math, Science, Reading along with the corresponding learning time.

  • The PISA zip file (325 MB) is provided on the Udacity learning site HERE.
  • Extract the zip file above, we have a csv file (2.75 GB) named pisa2012.csv.
  • Details about the data dictionary can be found HERE.

            'Post Secondary', 'Vocational Tertiary', 'Post Graduate']

# Return all educational levels with categories and orders
ed_levels = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=ed_parents)

# Convert the 2 educational columns into an ordered categorical type
df_copy['father_education'] = df_copy['father_education'].astype(ed_levels)
df_copy['mother_education'] = df_copy['mother_education'].astype(ed_levels)

1. Distribution of Scores¶

The dataset includes subject scores in mathematics, science, and reading, which vary between 200 and 800. All histogram of scores follows a clear normal distribution. The total scores also exhibit a normal distribution pattern, suggesting that the scores might have undergone standardization.

In [4]:
# Create a function to plot histograms
def histogram (col, binsize, xlabel=None):
    bins = np.arange(0, df_copy[col].max()+binsize, binsize)
    plt.hist(data = df_copy, x = col, bins = bins)
    plt.title('{}'.format(col.replace('_', ' ').title()))
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel('Student Count')
    plt.axvline(x = df_copy[col].median(), color = 'red')
    
# Set the plot dimensions
plt.figure(figsize = [14, 10])

# Create a dictionary to map positions with columns
scores_dict = {1:'math_score', 2:'science_score', 3:'reading_score', 4:'total_score'}

# Plot
for pos, col in scores_dict.items():
    plt.subplot(2, 2, pos)
    if pos == 4:
        histogram(col, binsize = 60, xlabel = 'Score')
    else:
        histogram(col, binsize = 30, xlabel = 'Score')

2. Distribution of Learning time¶

All distributions are right-skewed. The peak for each subject's learning time is about 180-220 minutes per week

In [5]:

# Create a dictionary to map positions with columns
learning_time_dict = {1:'learning_math_time', 2:'learning_science_time', 3:'learning_language_time', 4:'total_learning_time'}

# Plot all histograms
for pos, col in learning_time_dict.items():
    plt.subplot(2, 2, pos)
    if pos == 4:
        histogram(col, binsize = 100, xlabel='mins per week')
        plt.xlim(0, 2000)
    else:
        histogram(col, binsize = 50, xlabel='mins per week')
        plt.xlim(0, 1000)

3. Scores by Gender¶

Overall, male and female students have similar total scores. Female students have better performance in Reading while male students perform slightly better in Math. Both genders perform equally well in Science.

4. Scores by OECD membership¶

OECD countries have better performance in all subjects than non-OECD countries.

5. Total score by parents' education¶

A similar trend can be seen between both parents with their children's total score. Students whose parents have higher level of education are more likely to perform better. But for parents with educational levels from Upper Secondary to Vocational Tertiary, the difference in their children's performance is less significant.

6. Correlation between Scores¶

All scores show a positive correlation, suggesting that if a student performs well in either of the 3 subjects, he or she also performs well in the other two. Notably, the graph about Math and Science has the highest level of density, so these two subjects have the strongest correlation.

7. Scores by Gender and OECD membership¶

Overall, OECD students tend to perform better than non-OECD students. On average, males perform better in Math while females perform better in Reading. However, for Science, the median score of females is higher in OECD countries but lower in non-OECD countries.

    else:
        ax.get_legend().remove()

8. Total learning time by Gender and OECD membership¶

While females and males have the same learning time in non-OECD countries, males have longer learning time than females in OECD countries. Interestingly, the learning time of female students in non-OECD countries is slightly longer than those from OECD countries.
